# Cursor AI Rules — Crypto Wallet App

## Project Overview
React 19 + TypeScript + ethers.js v6 crypto wallet dashboard with:
- MetaMask wallet connection (via custom WalletContext, NOT react-moralis)
- Token balance fetching (ERC-20 + native)
- CoinGecko market data (top 50 coins)
- Tabbed UI: Wallet | Market

## Tech Stack
- React 19, TypeScript 4.9, ethers.js v6.17
- CSS custom properties with glassmorphism dark theme
- No state management library — Context API + hooks only
- react-scripts (CRA) for build

## Code Conventions
- Components: `FunctionComponent` type, default exports
- Hooks: custom hooks in `src/hooks/`, file prefix `use*`
- Context: `src/contexts/`, custom provider + hook pattern
- CSS: BEM-like naming with `__` for elements, `--` for modifiers
- Types: interfaces in `src/types/index.ts`
- Constants: extracted to `src/constants/`
- Imports: relative paths (NO `@/` aliases — CRA doesn't support them)

## File Structure Rules
- Each component in its own folder with `.tsx` + `.css`
- Sub-components nested within parent folder
- Barrel exports (`index.ts`) for multi-file modules

## Forbidden
- NO `react-moralis` or `moralis` (deprecated, removed)
- NO `@` path aliases (CRA breaks with them)
- NO inline styles (use CSS classes)
- NO `any` types without eslint-disable comment
- NO bare `fetch()` without AbortController

## Patterns
- `memo()` on components that don't change often (CoinRow, TokenBalances)
- `React.lazy()` + `Suspense` for tab content (Market is lazy-loaded)
- `useCallback` for event handlers passed as props
- `useRef` for mount tracking + fetch cancellation
- `Promise.allSettled` for parallel data fetching

## Commands
- `npm start` — dev server (port 3000)
- `npm run build` — production build
- `npm run lint` — ESLint
- `npm run format` — Prettier